between drama and ritual. By discussing historiographical theories of early modern Europe, especially those of Hans Blumenberg and Bruno Latour, and through conversations with Shakespearean drama and Spanish Golden Age classics, Vangshardt also argues that the theatrum mundi of celebration questions traditional assumptions of great divides between the Middle Ages and Early Modernity and challenges theories of a European-wide early modern sense of crisis.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aCalderón de la Barca, Pedro. 4aEuropa/Frühe Neuzeit. 4aSpanien/Goldenes Zeitalter. 4aWelttheater. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aEarly Modern Europe.  aGolden Age Spain.  aPedro Calderón de la Barca.  aTheatrum Mundi.  aWorld Theater.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1z97831113321920 cEPUBz97815015170200 cprintz978150152717340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150151700640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501517006423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501517006/original  a978-3-11-133219-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2024 Part 1b2024  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles